# Coding Conventions

## Single Responsibility

Each function should have a single dependency/responsibility. Break complex functions into smaller, focused units.

```typescript
// BAD - multiple responsibilities
function processUserData(user: User) {
  const validated = validateUser(user);
  const formatted = formatForDisplay(validated);
  saveToDatabase(formatted);
  sendNotification(user.email);
}

// GOOD - single responsibility per function
function processUserData(user: User) {
  const validated = validateUser(user);
  return formatForDisplay(validated);
}
```

## Comments

Only add comments that explain WHY, not WHAT. The code should be self-documenting.

```typescript
// BAD - redundant
// Loop through users
for (const user of users) { ... }

// GOOD - explains intent
// Skip inactive users to avoid sending emails to stale accounts
const activeUsers = users.filter(u => u.lastLogin > cutoffDate);
```

## Custom Hooks

Extract reusable logic into custom hooks. If logic doesn't need to be in the component, move it out.

```typescript
// BAD - logic cluttering component
function UserProfile() {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  useEffect(() => { /* fetch logic */ }, []);
  // ...
}

// GOOD - encapsulated in hook
function UserProfile() {
  const { data, loading } = useUserData(userId);
  // ...
}
```

## UI Components

Use shadcn/ui components as the base library. Extend them rather than building from scratch.

## Imports

Always remove unused imports. Keep import sections clean.
